<section xml:id="sec-3-4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Higher Order Linear Differential Equations</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Learn solution techniques for higher order linear differential equations
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <introduction>
    <p> In this section we discuss methods for solving the <m>n^\text{th}</m> order linear
      differential equations of the form <men xml:id="eq-nonhomogeneous2">
        y^{(n)} + a_{n-1}(x)y^{(n-1)} + \cdots + a_1(x)y' + a_0(x)y = f(x),
      </men>
      where the coefficient functions <m>a_0(x), \dots, a_{n-1}(x)</m> and the forcing term <m> f(x)</m>
      are continuous on some interval <m>I .</m>
    </p>
  </introduction>


  <subsection xml:id="subsection-3-4-1">
    <title>Homogeneous Equations</title>

    <p> To find the general solution of <xref ref="eq-nonhomogeneous2" />, we first find the general
      solution <m>y_h</m> of the associated homogeneous equation <men xml:id="eq-homogeneous2">
      y^{(n)} + a_{n-1}(x)y^{(n-1)} + \cdots + a_1(x)y' + a_0(x)y = 0
      </men> and a
      particular solution <m>y_p</m> of <xref ref="eq-nonhomogeneous2" />. Then the general solution
      of the nonhomogeneous equation <xref ref="eq-nonhomogeneous2" /> is given by <men
        xml:id="eq-general-solution">
        \boxed{ \begin{split}y &amp;= y_h(x)+y_p(x)\\ &amp; = c_1 y_1(x) + c_2 y_2(x) + \cdots + c_n
      y_n(x) + y_p(x)\end{split}}
      </men>
      on <m>I,</m> where <m>\{y_1, y_2, \dots, y_n\}</m> is a fundamental set of solutions of <xref
        ref="eq-homogeneous2" /> and <m>c_1, \dots, c_n</m> are arbitrary constants. The function <m>
      y_h(x),</m> also denoted by <m>y_c(x),</m> is called the <term>
        <em>complimentary function</em>
      </term> of the general solution of <xref
        ref="eq-homogeneous2" />. The existence of a fundamental set of solutions for <xref
        ref="eq-homogeneous2" /> follows by arguments analogous to those used in <xref
        ref="thm-existence-fundamental-solution-set" />. In fact, let <m>y_i</m> be the unique
      solution of the initial value problem consisting of the equation <xref ref="eq-homogeneous2" />
      subject to the initial conditions <men xml:id="eq-initial-conditions">
        y(x_0) =0, \dots, y^{(i-1)}(x_0) =1, \dots, y^{(n-1)}(x_0) =0, \end{equation}
      </men>
      where <m>i = 1, \dots, n.</m> It follows that <m>\{y_1, \dots, y_n\}</m> is a fundamental
      solutions of <xref ref="eq-homogeneous2" /> (see <xref ref="exercise-3-4-4" /> in <xref
        ref="exercises-EX34" />). </p>

    <p> Let <m>y_1, \dots, y_n</m> be solutions of <xref ref="eq-homogeneous2" />. In <xref
        ref="exercise-3-4-5" /> in <xref ref="exercises-EX34" />, you will derive the Abel formula
      for the Wronskian of <m>y_1, \dots, y_n</m> as <me>
        W(y_1, \dots, y_n) (x)= W(y_1, \dots, y_n)(x_0) e^{\int_{x_0}^x a_{n-1}(t)\, dt}, \; x\in I.
      </me>
    </p>

    <p> The linear independence of solutions <m>y_1, y_2, \dots, y_n</m> of <xref
        ref="eq-homogeneous2" /> can be determined using their Wronskian (see <xref
        ref="def-wronskian-n" />), as stated in the following theorem. </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-wronskian-nonzero-3">
      <statement>
        <p> Let <m>y_1, y_2, \dots, y_n</m> be solutions of <xref ref="eq-homogeneous2" /> on <m>I.</m>
          Then they are linearly independent on <m>I</m> if and only if <me>
            W(y_1, \dots, y_n)(x)\ne 0 \mbox{ for all } x \mbox{ in } I.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>


    <proof>
      <p> The proof is similar to the proof of <xref ref="thm-wronskian-nonzero-2" /> and is
        omiited. </p>
    </proof>

    <p> Methods for constructing a fundamental set of solutions for <xref ref="eq-homogeneous2" />
      vary. When we have means to find a single nonzero solution, the reduction of order discussion in <xref
        ref="sec-3-2" />  can be employed to obtain additional linearly
      independent solutions. This method applies not only to second order homogeneous linear
      equations but also extends to higher order equations, as discussed in the next theorem. </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-reduction-of-order-2">
      <statement>
        <p> Let <m>y_1</m> be a solution of <xref ref="eq-homogeneous2" /> such that <m>y_1(x)\ne 0</m>
          on <m>I,</m> and let <m>y = u y_1</m> be a solution of <xref ref="eq-homogeneous2" /> for
          a nonconstant function <m>u</m> on <m>I.</m> If <me>
            \{v_1, \dots, v_{n-1}\}
          </me> is a fundamental set of solutions for
          the equation of order <m>n-1</m> in <m>v=u'</m> obtained by substituting <m>y= u y_1</m>
          into <xref ref="eq-homogeneous2" /> and if <m>u'_k= v_k</m> for <m>k = 1, \dots, n-1,</m>
          then <me>
            \{y_1, u_1y_1, u_2y_1, \dots, u_{n-1}y_1\}
          </me> forms a
          fundamental set of solutions for <xref ref="eq-homogeneous2" /> on <m>I.</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>


    <proof>
      <p> We present a proof for the case <m>n=3.</m> The general case proceeds in a similar way,
        and a careful reader is encouraged to verify it, noting that it involves the use of binomial
        coefficients that are produced for higher order derivatives of the product function <m>y= u
        y_1.</m>
      </p>

      <p> For <m>y= uy_1</m> to be a solution of <xref ref="eq-homogeneous2" />, we must have <me>
        \begin{split} &amp;u'''y_1+ 3u''y'_1+ 3u'y''_1 + uy'''_1\\ &amp;+a_2 u''y_1+2a_2
        u'y'_1+a_2uy''_1\\ &amp;+a_1u'y_1+a_1uy'_1\\ &amp;+a_0uy_1 =0, \end{split}
        </me>
        which gives <me>
          \begin{split} &amp;u'''y_1+ (3y'_1+a_2y_1) u''+ (3y''_1+2a_2y'_1+a_1y_1)u'\\ &amp;+
        (y'''_1+a_2y''_1+a_1y'_1+a_0y_1)u=0 \end{split}
        </me>
        Since <m>y_1</m> is a solution of <xref ref="eq-homogeneous2" />, we have <m>
        y'''_1+a_2y''_1+a_1y'_1+a_0y_1=0.</m> Consequently, we obtain <me>
          u'''y_1+ (3y'_1+a_2y_1) u''+ (3y''_1+2a_2y'_1+a_1y_1)u'=0.
        </me> Letting <m>v=
        u'</m> gives <me>
          v''y_1+ (3y'_1+a_2y_1) v'+ (3y''_1+2a_2y'_1+a_1y_1)v=0,
        </me> which is a
        second order homogeneous linear equation in <m>v.</m> Suppose that <m>\{v_1, v_2\}</m> is a
        fundamental set of solution of the second order equation and let <m>u_k</m> be functions
        satisfying <m>u'_k = v_k,\; k = 1, 2.</m> To show <me>
          \{y_1, u_1y_1, u_2y_1 \}
        </me> is a fundamental set of solutions for <xref
          ref="eq-homogeneous2" />, let <m>c_0, c_1, c_2</m> be real numbers such that <me>
          c_0y_1(x) +c_1u_1(x) y_1(x) + c_2 u_2(x) y_1(x) = 0
        </me> for all <m>x</m>
        in <m>I.</m> Since <m>y_1(x) \ne 0</m> on <m>I,</m> we must have <me>
          c_0 +c_1u_1(x) + c_2 u_2(x) = 0
        </me> for all <m>x</m> in <m>I.</m>
        Differentiating yields <me>
          c_1u'_1(x) + c_2u'_2(x) = 0
        </me> for all <m>x</m> in <m>I,</m> that is, <me>
        c_1v_1(x) + c_2v_2(x) = 0
        </me> for all <m>x</m> in <m>I.</m> The linear
        independence of <m>\{v_1, v_2\}</m> on <m>I</m> implies that <m>c_1 = c_2 = 0.</m>
        Consequently, <m>c_0 = 0</m> as well. Therefore, <me>
          \{y_1,\, u_1 y_1,\, u_2 y_1\}
        </me> forms a linearly independent set of
        solutions of <xref ref="eq-homogeneous2" /> for <m>n = 3,</m> and hence constitutes a
        fundamental set of solutions. â—» </p>
    </proof>

    <example xml:id="example-reduction-order-1">
      <statement>
        <p> Find a fundamental set of solutions for <men xml:id="eq-reduction-order-1">
          y^{(4)}-4y'''+6y''-4y'+y=0,
          </men> given that <m>y= e^x</m> is a
          solution. Also, write down the general solution. </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p> Let <m>y= ue^x</m> a solution of <xref ref="eq-reduction-order-1" />, where <m>u</m> is
          a nonconstant function on <m>(-\infty, \infty).</m> Differentiating four times and
          substituting into the equation gives <me>
            \begin{split} &amp;u^{(4)}e^x+ 4u'''e^x+ 6u''e^x + 4u'e^x+ ue^x\\ &amp;-4u'''e^x
          -12u''e^x-12u'e^x -4 ue^x\\ &amp;+6u''e^x +12u'e^x+6 ue^x\\ &amp;-4u'e^x -4ue^x \\
          &amp;+ue^x =0.
            \end{split}
          </me>
          After canceling terms, we obtain <m>u^{(4)}e^x=0,</m> which yields <m>u^{(4)}(x)=0</m> in <m>(-\infty,
          \infty).</m> Let <m>v= u'.</m> Then we find <m>v'''(x) = 0</m> on <m>I.</m> Integrating,
          we obtain <me>
            v(x) = Ax^2+ Bx + C,
          </me> where <m>A, B, C</m> are arbitrary
          constants. </p>

        <p> Take <m>v_1(x) = 1, v_2(x)= 2x,</m> and <m>v_3(x)= 3x^2.</m> Then <m>\{v_1, v_2, v_3\}</m>
          forms a fundamental set of solutions for <m>v'''(x) = 0</m> on <m>I.</m> Since <m>u'=v,</m>
          we take <m>u_1(x) = x, u_2(x) = x^2,</m> and <m>u_3(x) =x^3,</m> so that <me>
            \{e^x, xe^x, x^2e^x, x^3 e^x\}
          </me> forms a fundamental set of
          solutions for <xref ref="eq-reduction-order-1" />. The general solution of the equation is <me>
          y= c_1e^x+c_2xe^x+c_3x^2e^x+c_4x^3 e^x = e^x(c_1+c_2x+c_3x^2+c_4x^3),
          </me>
          where <m>c_1, c_2, c_3, \text{ and } c_4</m> are arbitrary constants. </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>


  <subsection xml:id="subsection-3-4-2">
    <title>Nonhomogeneous Equations</title>

    <p> To find a particular solution <m>y_p(x)</m> of <xref ref="eq-nonhomogeneous2" /> by using
      the method of variation of parameters, we take <m>y_p(x)</m> as <men xml:id="eq-particular">
      y_p(x) = u_1(x)y_1(x) + u_2(x)y_2(x) + \cdots + u_n(x)y_n(x),
      </men> where <m>u_1(x),
      u_2(x), \dots, u_n(x)</m> are to be determined. </p>

    <p> Differentiating <xref ref="eq-particular" /> successively, and to simplify calculations,
      imposing the conditions <me>
        \begin{split} u_1'y_1 + u_2'y_2 + \cdots + u_n'y_n &amp;= 0, \\ u_1'y_1' + u_2'y_2' + \cdots
      + u_n'y_n' &amp;= 0, \\ &amp;\vdots \\ u_1'y_1^{(n-2)} + u_2'y_2^{(n-2)} + \cdots +
      u_n'y_n^{(n-2)} &amp;= 0, \end{split}
      </me>
      we obtain <me>
        u_1'y_1^{(n-1)} + u_2'y_2^{(n-1)} + \cdots + u_n'y_n^{(n-1)} = f(x).
      </me>
      These <m>n</m> equations can be solved for <m>u_1', u_2', \dots, u_n'</m> by using Cramer's
      rule as follows. We first write down the system of <m>n</m> equations in the matrix form <men
        xml:id="eq-matrixform-variation-of-parameters">
        \begin{bmatrix} y_1 &amp; y_2 &amp; \cdots &amp; y_n \\ y_1' &amp; y_2' &amp; \cdots &amp;
      y_n' \\ \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\ y_1^{(n-1)} &amp; y_2^{(n-1)} &amp;
      \cdots &amp; y_n^{(n-1)} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} u_1' \\ u_2' \\ \vdots \\ u_n'
      \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ \vdots \\ f(x) \end{bmatrix},
      </men>
      which can be solved for <m>u_1', u_2', \dots, u_n'</m> by using <term>Cramerâ€™s rule</term>. In
      fact, we have <me>
        u'_j= \frac{W_j}{W},
      </me> where <m>W</m> is the Wronskian of <m>y_1, \dots,
        y_n</m> and <m>W_k</m> is the determinant obtained by replacing the <m>j-</m>th column of <m>
      W</m> by the column on the right-hand side of <xref
        ref="eq-matrixform-variation-of-parameters" />. We find <me>
        u_j(x) =\int \frac{W_j(x)}{W(x)}\, dx
      </me> for each <m>j = 1, \dots, n</m> and
      hence <m>y_p(x)</m> is then fully determined by <xref ref="eq-particular" />. </p>

    <p> As discussed in <xref ref="re-variational-over-undertermined-coefficients" />, the method of
      variation of parameters is quite general and works for any linear nonhomogeneous differential
      equation (even with variable coefficients), so long as the required integrals for <m>u_1, u_2,
      \dots, u_n</m> make sense. </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p> Find the general solution of <me>
            y''' + y' = \tan x
          </me> by using the variation of parameters. </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p> The homogeneous equation associated to the nonhomogeneous equation <m>y''' + y' = \tan x</m>
          is <me>
            y''' + y' = 0
          </me> with the auxiliary equation <me>
            r^3 + r = 0 \quad \text{ so that } \quad r(r^2 + 1) = 0.
          </me> Then
          we have <me>
            r = 0, \quad r = i, \quad r = -i,
          </me> and therefore the functions <me>
          y_1(x) = 1, \quad y_2(x) = \sin x, \quad y_3(x) = \cos x
          </me> form a
          fundamental set of solutions for the homogeneous equation. The general solution to <m>y'''+y=
          \tan x</m> is then given by <me>
            y(x) = c_1 + c_2 \sin x + c_3 \cos x + y_p(x),
          </me> where <m>
          y_p(x)</m> is a particular solution of the nonhomogeneous equation. </p>

        <p> By the method of variation of parameters, we assume that <m>y_p(x)</m> is of the form <me>
          y_p(x) = u_1(x) + u_2(x) \sin x + u_3(x) \cos x,
          </me> where the
          functions <m>u_1, u_2, u_3</m> are to be determined so that <m>u_1', u_2', u_3'</m>
          satisfy </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            \begin{cases} u_1' + u_2' \sin x + u_3' \cos x = 0, \\[6pt] u_2' \cos x - u_3' \sin x =
          0, \\[6pt] u_2' \sin x - u_3' \cos x= \tan x.
            \end{cases}
          </me>
          The system in the matrix form is <me>
            \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; \sin x &amp; \cos x \\ 0 &amp; \cos x &amp; -\sin x \\ 0 &amp;
          -\sin x &amp; -\cos x \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} u_1' \\ u_2' \\ u_3' \end{bmatrix} =
          \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ \tan x \end{bmatrix}.
          </me>
          The Wronskian <m>W(x)</m> of <m>1, \sin x, \cos x</m> is <me>
            W(x) = \begin{vmatrix} 1 &amp; \sin x &amp; \cos x\\[6pt] 0 &amp; \cos x &amp; -\sin x
          \\[6pt] 0 &amp; -\sin x &amp; -\cos x \end{vmatrix}.
          </me>
          Using the co-factor expansion along the first column, we have <me>
            W(x) = \begin{vmatrix} \cos x &amp; -\sin x \\[6pt] -\sin x&amp; -\cos x \end{vmatrix}\\
          = -\cos^2 x - \sin^2 x\\ = -1.
          </me>
          We compute <me>
            W_1(x) = \begin{vmatrix} 0 &amp; \sin x &amp; \cos x\\[6pt] 0 &amp; \cos x&amp; -\sin x
          \\[6pt] \tan x &amp; -\sin x &amp; -\cos x \end{vmatrix}
          </me>
          by expanding along the first column and obtain <me>
            W_1(x) = \tan x \begin{vmatrix} \sin x &amp; \cos x \\[6pt] \cos x &amp; -\sin x
          \end{vmatrix} = \tan x( -\sin^2 x- \cos^2 x ) = -\tan x.
          </me>
          Then we have <me>
            u_1' = \frac{W_1}{W} = \frac{ -\tan x }{ -1 } = \tan x,
          </me> and
          consequently, we can take <me>
            u_1(x) = -\ln\lvert{\cos x}\rvert.
          </me> We next compute <me>
            W_2(x) = \begin{vmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 &amp; \cos x \\[6pt] 0 &amp; 0 &amp; -\sin x\\[6pt] 0
          &amp; \tan x&amp; -\cos x \end{vmatrix}
          </me>
          by expanding along the first column and obtain <me>
            W_2(x) = \begin{vmatrix} 0 &amp; -\sin x \\[6pt] \tan x &amp; -\cos x \end{vmatrix} = 0
            - (-\sin x) \tan x = \sin x \tan x.
          </me>
          Then we have <me>
            u_2' = \frac{W_2}{W} = \frac{ \sin x \tan x }{ -1 } = -\sin x \tan x
          =-\frac{\sin^2x}{\cos x}= \cos x- \sec x,
          </me>
          and so <me>
            u_2(x) = \int \big(\cos x- \sec x\big)\, dx.
          </me> We can take <me>
          u_2(x)= \sin x- \ln\lvert{\sec x+\tan x}\rvert.
          </me> We also compute <me>
          W_3(x) = \begin{vmatrix} 1 &amp; \sin x &amp; 0 \\[6pt] 0 &amp; \cos x &amp; 0 \\[6pt] 0
          &amp; -\sin x &amp; \tan x \end{vmatrix}
          </me>
          by expanding along the first column and obtain <me>
            W_3(x) = \begin{vmatrix} \cos x &amp; 0 \\[6pt] -\sin x &amp; \tan x \end{vmatrix} =
            \cos x \tan x = \sin x,
          </me>
          and so <me>
            u_3' = \frac{W_3}{W} = \frac{ \cos x \tan x }{ -1 } = - \sin x.
          </me>
          We can take <me>
            u_3(x) = \cos x.
          </me> Consequently, <m>y_p</m> is given by <me>
          \begin{aligned} y_p(x) &amp;= u_1(x) + u_2(x) \sin x + u_3(x) \cos x\\ &amp;=
          \ln\lvert{\sec x}\rvert+ \sin x\big(\sin x-\ln\lvert{\sec x+\tan x}\rvert\big)+\cos^2(x)\\
          &amp;=1+\ln\lvert{\sec x}\rvert-\sin x\ln\lvert{\sec x+\tan x}\rvert.
            \end{aligned}
          </me>
          Hence the general solution to <m>y'''+y' = \tan x</m> is <me>
            y(x) = c_1 + c_2 \sin x + c_3 \cos x +\ln\lvert{\sec x}\rvert-\sin x\ln\lvert{\sec
            x+\tan x}\rvert,
          </me>
          where <m>c_1</m>, <m>c_2</m> and <m>c_3</m> are arbitrary constants. </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-EX34">
    <exercise xml:id="exercise-3-4-1">
      <p>
        Find the general solution of each differential equation below by using variation of
        parameters to find a particular solution.
      </p>

      <ol marker="i." cols="2">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>y'''+y' = x+\sin x</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>y'''+4y' = \tan(2x)</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>y'''+y' = \cot x</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>y'''+9y' = \csc(3x)</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="exercise-3-4-2">
      <p>
        Solve each differential equation below by using the provided fundamental set of solutions
        for the associated homogeneous equation to find a particular solution by variation of
        parameters.
      </p>

      <ol marker="i.">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>x^3 y'''-x^2 y''+2 x y'+2y =-\frac{1}{x},\;\quad \{x, x^2, x \, \ln x\}</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>x^3 y'''+x^2 y''-2 x y'+2 y=-\frac{1}{x^2},\;\quad \{x, x^2, 1/x\}</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>xy'''-y''-xy'+y = 4x^2 e^x,\; \quad \{x, e^x, e^{-x}\}</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>x^3 y'''-(x+3) x^2 y''+2 (x+3) x y'-2 (x+3) y=x^5,\;\quad \{x, x^2, x \, \ln x\}</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>x^4 y^{(4)}+4 x^3 y'''+x^2 y''+x y'-y=\ln x,\; \quad \{1/x, x, x \ln x, x (\ln x)^2\}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="exercise-3-4-3">
      <p>
        Find a fundamental set of solutions for each differential equation below by using the given
        solution for the reduction of order.
      </p>

      <ol marker="i.">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>y^{(4)}-6 y'''+13 y''-12 y'+4y=0,\; \quad y_1(x) =e^x</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>x^3 y'''-x^2 y''+2 x y'+2y =0,\;\quad y_1(x) =x</m> for <m>x&gt;0</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>x^3 y'''+x^2 y''-2 x y'+2 y=0,\;\quad y_1(x)=x</m> for <m>x&gt;0</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>xy'''-y''-xy'+y = 0,\; \quad y_1(x)=x</m> for <m>x&gt;0</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="exercise-3-4-4">
      <p> Following the arguments similar to the proof of <xref
          ref="thm-existence-fundamental-solution-set" />, prove that the solutions <m>y_1, \dots,
        y_n</m> of the initial value problems consisting of the equation <xref ref="eq-homogeneous2" />
        and <m>n</m> initial conditions <xref ref="eq-initial-conditions" /> are linearly
        independent on <m>I.</m>
      </p>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="exercise-3-4-5">
      <p> Let <m>y_1, \dots, y_n</m> be solutions of <xref ref="eq-homogeneous2" />. Following the
        arguments used to derive <xref ref="eq-Abel-formula" />, prove that the Wronskian <m>W(y_1,
        \dots, y_n)</m> is given by <me>
          W(y_1, \dots, y_n)(x) = W(y_1, \dots, y_n)(x_0) \; e^{\int_{x_0}^x a_{n-1}(t)\, dt},\quad
        x\in I.
        </me>
      </p>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>
</section>